{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GaqkmvpoC2v3Ec4LNMi7w6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does the failure appear only at a module boundary? The question is whether explicit content detection works. If we mock the AI vision model, we'd just be testing routing logic. The real failure is whether the AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - this depends on what the AI vision model produces. Does the model correctly classify explicit images? This is an AI/ML model call.\n- The correctness here depends on the AI vision model's output quality (classification accuracy).\n\n\n- Minimum level: Agentic\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques.**\n\n- LLM-DEP: Yes - this depends on the AI text model's ability to detect obfuscated hate speech. This is testing model output quality - can the model detect letter substitution, unicode lookalikes, etc.\n- MOCK-MISS: A mock would always return the same result, hiding whether the model can actually handle obfuscation.\n- Minimum level: Agentic\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\n- This is testing the routing logic after content checks pass, so it's not dependent on model quality.\n- MOCK-MISS: A mock would hide whether the orchestration code correctly routes a clean post to publish.\n- LLM-DEP: We could stub both models to return clean and verify the system publishes, since we're testing the decision path for known-clean results.\n- Minimum level: Integration (wiring of modules with stubbed AI responses)\n\nFor Behavior 4, I'm thinking about whether latency testing requires real infrastructure or if mocks would work. With real model calls, we'd get actual latency, but with mocks we'd only measure the orchestration overhead. The question is whether that's sufficient to validate the 5-second requirement. 'd only be testing the overhead of the orchestration code.\n- The 5-second SLA includes the time for real AI model calls.\n- LLM-DEP: The actual latency depends on real AI model response times.\n- MULTI-STEP: This involves the full pipeline - multiple agentic steps.\n- This is a Workflow-level test because it requires multiple real agentic steps (image check + text check + publish decision) and the timing SLA depends on real AI/ML API call latencies.\n\nThe core issue is whether stubs can meaningfully test this. Using zero-latency stubs would trivially pass the test, and even realistic simulated delays don't capture actual AI model behavior. Real performance testing of the full pipeline with actual AI calls is what determines if we meet the 5-second SLA, since the failure mode depends on both real model latency and orchestration overhead. So this has to be Workflow-level.\n\nFor the vision model unavailability scenario, I need to think about whether I can simulate that failure mode with mocks or if I need real infrastructure to test it properly. stub that throws an error? Yes, we can stub the AI vision model to return an error/exception.\n- LLM-DEP: No - we're testing the error handling path, not model output quality. We just need the model to fail (return error), which we can simulate deterministically.\n- The question is: does this need real infrastructure or can it be tested with an in-process stub?\n\nActually, the behavior is about retry queue behavior when the model is unavailable. This tests:\n1. Error detection (model unavailable)\n2. Queuing for retry (not auto-approving)\n\nThis is testing the error handling/resilience logic. A stub that simulates \"model unavailable\" (throws ConnectionError, etc.) and verifying the post is queued for retry - this could be Integration level.\n\nBut wait - does this need real queue infrastructure? If the system uses a message queue like SQS or RabbitMQ, I could use either a real queue or an in-process fake. The key is verifying the queueing behavior works when the model fails. With stubs for both the AI model and the queue, I can test this at the Integration level without needing real infrastructure.\n\nThe orchestration code routing to the retry queue on failure is what matters here - multiple modules working together with fakes, so this lands at Integration.\n\nFor behavior 6, I'm looking at consistency of the moderation decision for borderline images across multiple submissions. This is fundamentally about AI model non-determinism - a mock would always return the same value, so it can't catch real inconsistency. I need actual AI model calls to see if the same borderline image produces different results. This requires the Agentic level because the behavior depends on real model behavior, not just system logic. which requires a real model. The word \"borderline\" is the critical detail here—it's testing whether the model wavers on edge cases, and a stub would mask that real non-determinism. So this is definitely Agentic level.\n\nNow let me map out my full analysis across all the test scenarios.\n\nFor each one, I'm assigning probability weights across the test levels. The explicit content case leans heavily toward Agentic since we need the actual model's classification quality, though there's a small chance it could work as Integration with a stubbed model. Hate speech with obfuscation is even more Agentic-heavy—that's where the model's robustness really matters. The clean post being published could arguably be Unit or Integration since it's mostly about orchestration logic, but Integration is more likely. And I'm working through the probability distributions for the remaining scenarios. Looking at behavior 3 more carefully—whether a post with both checks passing actually gets published—I realize this needs to be an integration test rather than just unit testing the decision logic. While I could test the decision function in isolation, that wouldn't catch if the publish call never actually executes, so I need to verify the full handoff from clean results through to the actual publish action. Unit: 0.20, Integration: 0.75.\n\nFor behavior 4 about the 5-second completion time, this is clearly a workflow test since it measures the entire pipeline end-to-end with real latency from the image check, text check, and publish decision all chained together.\n\nNow I'm working through the test descriptions for each behavior, starting with how to verify the explicit content routing and then the obfuscation handling for text-based hate speech.\n\nFor the remaining tests, I need to verify the happy path where both checks pass and the system publishes, then run an end-to-end timing assertion against the full pipeline with real model calls. I also want to test the error handling when the vision model fails to ensure posts go to retry rather than being auto-approved, and finally validate that the vision model returns consistent decisions when the same borderline image is submitted repeatedly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9685,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9685},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3f650877-d57c-4a84-bac7-dd72b9212d40","uuid":"16d708bc-a172-4baf-99bc-468944f2cbe0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GaqkmvpoC2v3Ec4LNMi7w6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017aK5g2gvXz6z59CK7xWEWS","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure boundary is whether the AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content — not whether the routing code runs. A stub always returns the same label, so it can never reveal that the model misclassifies explicit material as clean. LLM-DEP: Model output quality (classification accuracy) determines correctness. REJECTION-GATE: A mock/stub was considered and rejected because it replaces the model's actual judgment with a constant, making any classification failure invisible. No behavior text disqualifies Agentic.","test_description":"Submit a curated set of known-explicit test images directly through the moderation pipeline using the real AI vision model. Assert that each image produces a 'flag' decision and the post is routed to the human-review queue, never to the publish path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The specific failure mode is whether the real AI text model can detect hate speech that has been obfuscated. A deterministic stub always returns the same result regardless of obfuscation, so any model-level weakness against unicode lookalikes or substitution ciphers is invisible. REJECTION-GATE: The word 'regardless of obfuscation techniques' directly asserts model robustness — a property only the real model can demonstrate. No disqualifying text removes the Agentic requirement.","test_description":"Construct a test corpus of hate speech samples in their original form plus multiple obfuscated variants (l33t-style substitution, homoglyph unicode, deliberate misspellings). Feed each sample to the real AI text model via the moderation pipeline and assert every variant is flagged, not published.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode here is orchestration: given 'clean' results from both checkers, does the routing layer actually invoke publish()? This is a module-boundary handoff bug, not a model-quality bug. LLM-DEP: Both checkers can be stubbed to return 'clean' deterministically — the assertion is about what the orchestration code does with those results, not what the models produce. REAL-INFRA: No real OS, network, or subprocess is needed; an in-process fake for each model plus a spy on the publish path is sufficient. REJECTION-GATE: 'silently dropped' implies we must verify the publish path is actually invoked (not just the decision is correct), which requires module wiring — but a stub-driven integration test fully catches that failure.","test_description":"Wire the image-check module and text-check module with stubs that return 'clean', connect them to the orchestrator, and submit a test post. Assert the orchestrator calls the publish path exactly once and does not invoke the hold or discard paths.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names three sequential stages (image check → text check → publish decision), which is a full agent pipeline. REAL-INFRA: End-to-end latency with stub models measures only orchestration overhead and is trivially fast, hiding any SLA violation that comes from real AI API call latency. LLM-DEP: Both AI model calls contribute their real round-trip time to the 5-second budget. REJECTION-GATE: A timed test with stubs always passes (sub-millisecond) and cannot reveal whether the real pipeline meets the SLA. The behavior must be tested with real model calls in sequence.","test_description":"Submit a realistic image-plus-text post to the full production pipeline using real AI vision and text model endpoints. Record wall-clock time from submission receipt to publish-or-hold decision. Assert elapsed time is under 5 seconds across at least N representative samples (including borderline cases that may trigger deeper model inference).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.13,"Workflow":0.75}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the error-handling branch of the orchestrator: when the vision model call raises a connection/timeout error, does the system enqueue the post or fall through to auto-approve? This is a module-boundary state transition, not a model quality issue. LLM-DEP: The 'unavailable' condition is deterministic — a stub that raises ConnectionError faithfully simulates it. REAL-INFRA: The retry queue can be an in-process fake; the failure (auto-approve instead of enqueue) is exposed entirely by checking which path the orchestrator takes after catching the error. REJECTION-GATE: Integration with a stubbed failing model and a fake queue fully captures the relevant failure; real network/infra failure is not required to observe the bug.","test_description":"Configure the AI vision model dependency with a stub that raises a service-unavailable exception on every call. Submit an image post through the orchestrator. Assert the post is placed on the retry queue and is not marked as approved or published. Verify no auto-approve flag is set on the queued item.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The failure mode is AI model non-determinism on borderline inputs. A stub always returns the same constant, so it trivially satisfies consistency without revealing real model variance (e.g., temperature-driven flip between 'flag' and 'pass' on an ambiguous image). MOCK-HIDE: Mocking guarantees consistency by construction, making this test always pass regardless of real model behavior. The word 'borderline' specifically signals cases where the model is near its decision boundary — the exact regime where non-determinism is most likely. REJECTION-GATE: No system-level caching or idempotency mechanism is mentioned in the behavior; the assertion is about 'moderation decision' consistency, which is a model output property, not an infrastructure property. Workflow is not required because only one model stage (vision) is exercised per submission.","test_description":"Select a set of borderline images (calibrated to sit near the model's classification threshold). Submit each image to the real AI vision model-backed pipeline at least 10 times in rapid succession. Assert that all 10 decisions for each image are identical (all 'flag' or all 'pass'), with no flip between decisions for the same image.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9685,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9685},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"3f650877-d57c-4a84-bac7-dd72b9212d40","uuid":"636051cb-50ac-48c5-b3d9-c851b2185c45"}
